radiographic_examinations.findings: Bibasilar atelectasis, trace bilateral pleural effusions, tiny pericardial effusion, relative hypoattenuation of the blood pool, dense calcifications in the mitral annulus. Interval placement of a percutaneous biliary drain with the tip of the catheter coiling within a partially collapsed gallbladder, slight hyperdensity of gallbladder contents, no evidence of gallbladder wall perforation, small amount of pneumobilia, unremarkable liver, pancreas, and spleen, tiny 1-mm radiodensity in the right renal interpole possibly representing a non-obstructing stone, unremarkable stomach and visualized portions of bowel, scattered calcifications in the abdominal aorta and splenic artery, and multilevel degenerative changes in the spine.
